Anonymous Mon 07 Jun 2021 05:46:14 No.39235128 Report
Quoted By: >>39235437 >>39236974
Oops. Repostan

>>39231329
You'd do well to have beta readers who can inform you of your readability, but also provide you solid advice as to what editing will help you meet your criterion for demographic appeal and palatability. Do you want it published here, on SoFurry, and/or on reddit?
This
>>39231615
is unironically useful advice. I'd say you want it to appeal to mid-twenty to thirty-somethings, drunk or sober; employ language and visuals that are vibrant & colorful, and worth getting excited about on a Friday night. The vaporwave aesthetic accomplishes this surprisingly well, so translate a palette like that into descriptive prose. That's more of an opinion, but hey, it worked for the MCU's most memorable films when they started rolling out with neon palettes and space opera themes galore.
In any case, with ten to twenty dollar words, use intuition—trust your instinct. If it sounds synonymous with something simpler, but rings out mellifluously when spoken aloud, just make sure to wrap it up succinctly in a way that makes that meaning clear; don't make your reader need a dictionary to enjoy your prose. If they're lit majors, sure; if they're furries, comers, and toppers looking for a rip-roaring adventure, a wamk, and something to talk about with their buds later on a Saturday, then dumb it down, or utilize s u b t e x t.

More than anything, have fun, and don't burn yourself out - have some writebros around to help you. Never gets better than that.

>>39235128
>solid advice as to what editing will help you meet your criterion for demographic appeal and palatability
It is also the job of the writer to dissect the comments of their beta/first readers. The person that knows the characters best is the writer, but opposing viewpoints are a whetstone instead of a marketing poll.

As for the original question, hard scifi is tough to write and moreso if you don't understand the scientific concept(s) that backstops your story.
It's easy to not say what you don't know, but really hard to not explain something and get all the surrounding details right.
That's why I hated the rash of CSI shows when they were on. The science was so bad it made 90s Star Trek look hard.
